Crystal Lake Metabolism

DO%sat and DO mass:

Figure 1. Volume weighted dissolved oxygen percent saturation (A) and total dissolved oxygen mass (B).

NEP:

Figure 2. Six-hourly depth integrated NEP (grey points) and 3 day moving median (red line). Missing data was filled with the monthly average before smoothing. NEP = delta.O2 - flux.O2, where delta.O2 is the change in the areal whole lake dissolved oxygen between consecutive 6 hour profiles, and flux.O2 is the O2 flux between the atmosphere and lake calculated every minute and integrated over the 6 hour period between profiles. The k.gas model used for calculation is Cole and Caraco 1998.

Figure 3. Six-hourly depth integrated NEP averaged to periods of stratification and mixing. Error bars denote standard error uncorrected for autocorrelation. Error bars for the period “before.strat.or.mix” are +- 21 mmol/m^2/6hr. The peiod “during.mix.before.strat” is the period after mixing began but before seasonal stratification was established. The start of stratification is defined as the day Schmidt Stability = 200 J/m^2 and is rapidly increasing, which roughly corresponds to a 2-4 m deep upper mixed layer of a 20 C temperature. The end of stratification is defined as the day Schmidt Stability = 200 J/m^2 and is rapidly decreasing.

Figure 3.2. Quartile plot of six-hourly depth integrated NEP grouped according to the description provided in figure 3.

Figure 4. Upper mixed layer NEP vs. depth integrated NEP for the full open water period. NEP is of six-hourly resolution. Dashed line is 1:1.

Figure 5. Upper mixed layer NEP vs. depth integrated NEP for the full open water period. NEP is of six-hourly resolution. Dashed line is 1:1. Solid line is the type II major axis regression. Regression equation and correlation coefficient are presented.

Figure 5.2. Upper mixed layer NEP vs. depth integrated NEP grouped by season. Spring = ice-off to summer solstice; Summer = summer solstice to fall equinox; Fall = fall equinox to mid-November. NEP is of six-hourly resolution. Dashed line is 1:1. Solid line is the type II major axis regression. Regression equation and correlation coefficient are presented.

GPP & R:

Figure 6. Upper mixed layer GPP vs. depth integrated GPP for the full open water period. Note data have been log transformed to meet assumptions of type II major axis regression. GPP is of daily resolution. Negative values of GPP have been omitted. Solid line is the type II major axis regression. Regression equation and correlation coefficient are presented.

Figure 5.2. Upper mixed layer GPP vs. depth integrated GPP grouped by season. Spring = ice-off to summer solstice; Summer = summer solstice to fall equinox; Fall = fall equinox to mid-November. GPP is of daily resolution. Negative values of GPP have been omitted. Data have been log transformed to meet assumptions of type II major axis regression. Solid line is the type II major axis regression. Regression equiation and correlation coefficient are presented.

Figure 7. Upper mixed layer R vs. depth integrated R for the full open water period. Note data have been log transformed to meet assumptions of type II major axis regression. R is of daily resolution. Days of bad estimates have been ommitted, where “bad” estimates are considered R < 0. Solid line is the type II major axis regression. Regression equation and correlation coefficient are presented.

Figure 7.2. Upper mixed layer R vs. depth integrated R grouped by season. R is of daily resolution. Days of bad estimates have been ommitted, where “bad” estimates are considered R < 0. Spring = ice-off to summer solstice; Summer = summer solstice to fall equinox; Fall = fall equinox to mid-November. Data have been log transformed to meet assumptions of type II major axis regression. Solid line is the type II major axis regression. Regression equiation and correlation coefficient are presented.
